# 7. Power Supplies

## Main Function

A PSU converts AC from the wall into DC used by computer components.

## Main Voltage Rails

### 3.3 V
Used by:

- RAM
- chipsets
- motherboard electronics

### 5 V
Used by:

- USB
- some storage electronics
- legacy devices

### 12 V
Used by:

- CPU
- GPU
- fans
- motors
- pumps

## Electrical Formula

Watts = Volts × Amps

## Regional Power

### United States
- around 110–120 V
- 60 Hz

### Europe
- around 220–240 V
- 50 Hz

## Auto Input Detection

Modern PSUs often automatically support different regional voltages.

## +5VSB

5-volt standby rail.

Provides limited power while the system is technically off.

Used for features such as:

- wake-on-LAN
- USB charging
- soft power button

## Modular PSU

Cables can be removed or added as needed.

Advantages:

- cleaner cable management
- improved airflow
- easier installation

## Redundant PSU

Two or more PSUs provide backup power.

## Hot-Swappable PSU

Can be replaced while the system remains running.

## 80 Plus

Efficiency certification.

Common order:

- 80 Plus
- Bronze
- Silver
- Gold
- Platinum
- Titanium

