# 10. Inkjet Printers

Inkjet printers spray tiny liquid-ink droplets onto paper.

## CMYK

- Cyan
- Magenta
- Yellow
- Key/Black

## Advantages

- inexpensive printer
- quiet
- good colour output
- good photo quality
- high resolution

## Disadvantages

- expensive ink
- print heads can clog
- ink can fade
- ink may dry out

## Maintenance

### Cleaning
Removes dried or excess ink.

Useful for:

- streaks
- missing lines
- blocked nozzles

### Calibration
Aligns colours and print-head placement.

---

# 11. Thermal Printers

Thermal printers use heat on thermochromic paper.

They do not use ink or toner.

## Common Uses

- receipts
- shipping labels
- barcode labels

## Advantages

- quiet
- simple
- inexpensive to operate
- few moving parts

## Maintenance

- use the correct paper roll
- clean the heating element with isopropyl alcohol
- use a cleaning card
- keep the paper path clean

Important receipts can fade from heat, light, or age.

---

# 12. Dot-Matrix Printers

Pins strike an inked ribbon to form characters and images.

## Common Uses

- multipart forms
- invoices
- industrial environments
- continuous paper

## Advantages

- can print through several paper layers
- low cost per page
- durable

## Disadvantages

- noisy
- low resolution
- slower than modern printers

## Common Parts

- print head
- pins
- ribbon cartridge
- tractor feed
- heat sink

## Troubleshooting

- faded output: replace ribbon
- missing dots/lines: failed print-head pin
- jams: check tractor-feed alignment and paper path

