# 13. Virtualization

Virtualization allows multiple operating systems to run on one physical computer.

## Virtual Machine

A software-based computer with:

- guest operating system
- virtual CPU
- allocated RAM
- virtual storage
- virtual network adapter

Resources come from the physical host.

## Host OS

The main operating system installed on the physical computer.

## Guest OS

The operating system running inside a VM.

## Snapshot

A saved point-in-time state of a VM.

Used to return to a known working state.

## Sandboxing

Running software in an isolated environment so problems stay contained.

## Hypervisor

Software that creates and manages VMs.

It allocates:

- CPU
- RAM
- storage
- networking

## Type 1 Hypervisor

Runs directly on physical hardware.

Also called a bare-metal hypervisor.

Examples:

- VMware ESXi
- Microsoft Hyper-V in bare-metal/server use

## Type 2 Hypervisor

Runs on top of a normal host OS.

Also called a hosted hypervisor.

Examples:

- VirtualBox
- VMware Workstation
- Parallels Desktop

## CPU Virtualization Support

- Intel: VT
- AMD: AMD-V

## VM Escape

Malware or an attacker exploits a hypervisor flaw and escapes one VM to reach:

- the host
- other VMs
- data outside the original VM

Each VM still needs:

- firewall
- updates
- anti-malware
- hardening
- strong passwords

## VDI

Virtual Desktop Infrastructure.

The user desktop runs on a remote server or in the cloud.

The local device mainly provides:

- display
- keyboard
- mouse
- network connection

## DaaS

Desktop as a Service.

A cloud-delivered virtual desktop service.

