# 14. Virtual Networking

## NAT

The VM is placed on a separate virtual subnet.

It reaches outside networks through address translation.

Outside devices normally see the host's address.

Use case:

- normal internet access for a VM
- software testing
- basic Linux practice

## Bridged Networking

The VM acts like another physical device on the real LAN.

It gets its own LAN IP address.

Use case:

- test server
- Active Directory lab
- SSH/RDP access
- communication with physical devices

## Private/Internal Networking

VMs communicate only with other selected VMs on the isolated virtual network.

Usually no internet or real-LAN access.

Use case:

- isolated attack lab
- malware analysis
- private SOC lab
- safe network experiments

